By late 2017, the Rare Pepe Directory included more than 1,700 cards.

There were themed collections, unique artists, jokes only the community understood, and even rivalries between owners.

All of this grew naturally - no ads, no hype.

It became the first true NFT community.

The Rare Pepe community even built its own tools.

Artists and collectors used the Rare Pepe Wallet, a simple but working marketplace.

There, they could view cards, connect their wallets, and trade NFTs with BTC, XCP, or $PepeCash.

It wasn’t advanced, but it did the job.

One card became a legend - HOMERPEPE, a weird mix of Pepe the Frog and Homer Simpson.

It was created in 2016, sold in 2018 for $39,000, and later sold again for over $320,000. 

A simple meme that quietly beat most altcoins and changed how we see internet art.

To be recognized, an artwork had to enter the Rare Pepe Directory, a curated list of approved pieces.

Submission required burning some $PepeCash, one of the first examples of community curation and digital scarcity. 

Long before DAOs, this was how rules were set.

These digital tokens were far more than jokes or collectibles. 

Each Rare Pepe was a unique piece of art with a limited edition supply, recorded directly on the blockchain. 

Some were issued as one-of-a-kind, while others became the object of desire for early collectors.
